<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="523" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,151,320]" pageId="22" pageNumber="523">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,224,248]" pageId="22" pageNumber="523">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[595,722,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Balclutha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="523" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saltuella">
<emphasis box="[595,722,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="523">B. saltuella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished from the latter by the five longitudinal brown bands on the pronotum and the bifurcated aedeagus apex. This species resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[1166,1260,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Balclutha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="523" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rosea">
<emphasis box="[1166,1260,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="523">B. rosea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except that the pronotal bands are brown, not orange, and the shape of the aedeagus is different.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
